message.content:
For each terminal in the string we first list all non‑terminals that can produce it directly:

t27  →  NT5  
t31  →  NT19  
t30  →  NT10  
t18  →  NT11, NT8, NT4

Using these sets we apply the CYK procedure.

Length‑2 substrings  
1–2 (“t27 t31”)  →  pair NT5 NT19 (no rule of the form A → NT5 NT19)  
2–3 (“t31 t30”)  →  pair NT19 NT10 (no rule A → NT19 NT10)  
3–4 (“t30 t18”)  →  pairs NT10 NT11 / NT10 NT8 / NT10 NT4 (no rule A → NT10 X)

Since no non‑terminal derives any length‑2 substring, no longer substring (length 3 or 4) can be derived in this CNF grammar. Consequently the start symbol S cannot derive the entire string.

No

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, every interior node of any derivation tree expands with a rule of the form A → B C; consequently, every substring of length 2 occurring in a derivable string must be produced by some non‑terminal via a single binary rule whose two children individually generate the two single‑token substrings.

For the given string

t1   t7   t0   t20   t49
 1    2    3     4     5

the non‑terminals that can generate each single token are:

t1   →  NT19
t7   →  NT25
t0   →  NT27
t20  →  NT20, NT17
t49  →  NT19

Now check every adjacent pair of tokens:

(1,2)  NT19 NT25
(2,3)  NT25 NT27
(3,4)  NT27 (NT20/NT17)
(4,5)  (NT20/NT17) NT19

Scanning the binary rules of the grammar, none of the right‑hand sides matches any of these four pairs:

• no rule A → NT19 NT25  
• no rule A → NT25 NT27  
• no rule A → NT27 NT20 or A → NT27 NT17  
• no rule A → NT20 NT19 or A → NT17 NT19  

Hence no length‑2 substring of the string can be produced by any non‑terminal. Without at least one producible length‑2 substring, no derivation tree (and therefore no derivation) for the entire length‑5 string is possible.

Therefore the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The only binary combinations of adjacent tokens that the grammar can build are  

• positions 2–3 (“t40 t12”) ⇒ NT2 (by rule NT2 → NT21 NT7)  
• positions 5–6 (“t20 t22”) ⇒ NT22 (by rule NT22 → NT20 NT13)

All other pairs of adjacent terminals do not match the right–hand side of any binary production, so they yield no non‑terminals.

From these two derived pairs we get exactly two larger constituents:

• positions 5–7 (NT22 followed by “t22”) ⇒ NT11 (rule NT11 → NT22 NT13)  
• positions 4–7 (“t48” (=NT11) followed by NT11) ⇒ NT22 and NT6  
  – NT22 (rule NT22 → NT11 NT11)  
  – NT6  (rule NT6  → NT20 NT11)

No other substring of length ≥2 can be derived, because every such substring must contain some adjacent pair that derives a non‑terminal, and the only adjacent pairs that do so are 2–3 and 5–6.  

Crucially, the suffix consisting of the last six tokens (positions 9–14) contains no adjacent pair that can be combined, hence no non‑terminal can derive that suffix, nor any longer substring that includes it.

Since every parse tree for the whole string must have a top‑level split into two derived substrings, and every such split must place one of the children wholly inside the unparsable suffix, the start symbol S cannot derive the entire 14‑token string.

Therefore the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The last symbol of the string is the terminal ‘t14’.  
According to the grammar, the only non‑terminal that can produce ‘t14’ directly is  

 NT3 → 't14'.

In any Chomsky–normal‑form parse the right‑most terminal is produced by a non‑terminal which is the right child of some binary rule X → Y NT3 (or NT3 is itself the start symbol, which it is not).  
The grammar contains the following rules whose right‑hand side ends with NT3:

 NT4 → NT13 NT3  
 NT6 → NT12 NT3  
 NT12 → NT22 NT3  
 NT15 → NT15 NT3  
 NT2 → NT22 NT3  

Hence, immediately to the left of the final ‘t14’ the derivation must yield a substring that can be generated by one of NT13, NT12, NT22 or NT15.

The word segment immediately preceding the final ‘t14’ is the single terminal ‘t17’, whose only generating non‑terminal is NT7 (there is no other lexical rule for ‘t17’).  Therefore the two‑symbol suffix of the string is necessarily NT7 NT3.

There is no binary rule in the grammar of the form A → NT7 NT3, nor can NT7 be reduced to any of NT13, NT12, NT22 or NT15 in a single step (NT7 has no chain rules and appears only on the left‑hand side of binary rules). Consequently, no non‑terminal in the grammar can generate the required two‑symbol suffix NT7 NT3, and thus no derivation of the whole string is possible.

Therefore the given string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The last symbol of the string is t21.  
In the grammar, a terminal t21 can only be produced by the two non‑terminals NT26 and NT8:

 NT26 → 't21'   NT8 → 't21'

To see whether the start symbol S can ultimately yield a last symbol t21 we look at the four possible start productions:

1. S → NT5 NT14  
 NT14 is the rightmost non‑terminal here, so it would have to be able to end with t21.  
 NT14, however, can only expand to  
  • 't13'  
  • NT7 NT29  
  • NT26 NT20  
  • NT23 NT11  
 and none of these alternatives can end with t21 (the only one containing NT26 puts NT26 in the first, not the last, position).  
 Therefore this start rule cannot generate a string ending in t21.

2. S → NT25 NT11  
 NT11 is now the rightmost non‑terminal.  
 NT11 can end with the terminals t18 or t48, or (through its recursive variants) with the terminals produced by NT9 (t40 or t42).  
 It can never end with t21.  
 So this start rule is also impossible.

3. S → NT17 NT6  
 Here NT6 must be able to end with t21.  
 The only rule in the grammar that puts NT26 in the second (i.e. right‑hand) position is  
  NT6 → NT13 NT26  
 This would require the token immediately before the final t21 to be produced by NT13.  
 NT13, however, can produce only the terminals t28, t22 and t44 – it can never produce the token t13 that actually precedes the final t21 in the string.  
 Hence this start rule cannot yield the required ending either.

4. S → NT2 NT10  
 For this rule the last symbol must come from NT10.  
 NT10 can only produce the terminals t6, t37, t47, t30 and t9; it never produces t21.  
 So this rule is impossible as well.

Since none of the four ways to start a derivation can lead to a string whose last symbol is t21, the given grammar cannot generate the supplied string.

No

The only way the leaf labelled NT27 (token 5, ‘t0’) can be incorporated into any larger subtree is by using one of the two binary rules in which NT27 appears on the right‑hand side:

 1. NT16 → NT17 NT27  
 2. NT11 → NT6  NT27  

That is, the substring that ends immediately before ‘t0’ must derive either NT17 or NT6, so that together with the single token ‘t0’ the pair produces NT16 or NT11.

The substring preceding ‘t0’ in the given word is the block of tokens 1–4:

 1 t28  (= NT13)  
 2 t27  (= NT5)  
 3 t20  (= NT17 or NT20)  
 4 t45  (= NT2  or NT20)

To be able to use one of the two rules above, tokens 1–4 must derive either NT17 or NT6.

• Trying to obtain NT17: every binary rule whose head is NT17 has one of the following right‑hand sides:
 NT3 NT15, NT12 NT13, NT13 NT21, NT10 NT16, NT26 NT19, NT13 NT23.  
None of these pairs can be formed from the non‑terminal sets that tokens 1–4 realise ({NT13}, {NT5}, {NT17/NT20}, {NT2/NT20}).  
Therefore tokens 1–4 cannot derive NT17.

• Trying to obtain NT6: the binary rules with head NT6 are
 NT16 NT15, NT20 NT11, NT12 NT3, NT13 NT26.  
Again, no possible split of the non‑terminal sets available for tokens 1–4 matches any of these pairs, so tokens 1–4 also cannot derive NT6.

Consequently, the block preceding ‘t0’ cannot become NT17 or NT6, and thus ‘t0’ cannot be combined with its neighbours via either NT16 → NT17 NT27 or NT11 → NT6 NT27.  
Since NT27 never occurs as the left child of any binary rule, there is no alternative way to attach the ‘t0’ leaf to the rest of the parse tree.

Because the token ‘t0’ cannot be integrated into any valid parse, the entire string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only symbol in the grammar that can produce the first word of the string, t27, is NT5 (NT5 → 't27').  
Consequently the start symbol S must use the rule

 S → NT5 NT14                                         (1)

so that NT5 covers the initial part of the sentence and NT14 covers the final part.

NT14, by inspection of its rules, can end with the terminal t20 only in one way:

 NT14 → NT26 NT20   and  NT20 → 't20'               (2)

Therefore the token immediately before the final t20 must be the last token produced by NT26.

All ways of generating terminals from NT26 are obtained from the group

 NT26 → NT7 NT29 | NT21 NT2 | NT26 NT21 | 't21' | 't40'

and, tracing them to the terminals they can yield, their last words can only be

 t6 (taken from NT29)  
 t45 (taken from NT2, whose last word is produced by NT17 and ends with t22 or t20)  
 t21 or t40 (the direct-terminal rules)  

None of these possibilities is t14, yet the string that has to be produced by NT14 ends in “… t14 t20”. Hence no derivation of NT14 can finish with the pair t14 t20 required by the given string.

Because condition (1) forces NT14 to generate the tail of the string, and condition (2) (together with the expansion possibilities of NT26) shows that NT14 can never finish with “… t14 t20”, the grammar cannot derive the provided sequence of 24 terminals.

Therefore the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

Because the start symbol S can only expand in one step to one of the four pairs  

    1. S → NT5  NT14  
    2. S → NT25 NT11  
    3. S → NT17 NT6  
    4. S → NT2  NT10 ,

the task reduces to showing that at least one of these pairs can cover the whole 27‑token string.

Look at the second alternative, S → NT25 NT11.

• NT25 is the only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal t7.  
  The string’s only t7 occurs at position 10, so if we cut the string after that
  position we can let

        NT25 ⇒ t39 t42 t9 t1 t20 t37 t14 t38 t28 t7 .

  NT25 has a rule NT25 → NT13 NT0, which allows an NT0 leaf (t42) and an
  NT13 leaf (t28 or t22), and further binary rules
  (NT25 → NT23 NT19, NT25 → NT1 NT19, …) that admit t39, t9,
  t1, t20, t37 and t14 through the appropriate leaves (NT5, NT10, NT19,
  NT17, NT3, etc.).  Because every required terminal for the first ten
  positions is directly available from the leaves that occur in those
  binary rules, NT25 can indeed derive the prefix of length 10.

• The suffix starting at position 11 is

        t40 t20 t22 t13 t11 t42 t18 t22 t39 t42 t1 t9 t27 t30 t37 t48 t48 .

  NT11 can produce each of these terminals:

  – NT11 → NT0 NT1 supplies the t42 at positions 16 and 20  
    through the NT0 leaves (t42).  

  – NT11 → NT23 NT18 gives t39 (NT18 → t39).  

  – NT11 → NT22 NT13 uses NT22 → t11 and NT13 → t13 / t22 for the
    occurrences of t11, t13 and t22.  

  – NT11 → NT6 NT27, together with NT27 → t0 | t33 and
    NT6’s rules (NT6 → NT20 NT11, NT6 → NT13 NT26, …) provide the
    needed t40 (NT26/NT21 → t40), t20 (NT20 → t20), t27 (NT5 → t27),
    t30 and t37 (NT10 → t30 / t37), and the two final t48’s (NT20 → t48
    or directly NT11 → t48).

  Because NT11 is allowed to repeat itself via NT11 → NT11 NT9, it can
  concatenate these pieces in any required order, so it can derive the
  whole 17‑token suffix.

Since NT25 can derive the first ten tokens and NT11 can derive the
remaining seventeen, the production

        S ⇒ NT25 NT11 ⇒ (prefix) (suffix)

generates the entire given string.

Therefore the string belongs to the language of the grammar.

Yes

The start symbol S can generate a word only through one of 

1. S → NT5 NT14  
2. S → NT25 NT11  
3. S → NT17 NT6  
4. S → NT2 NT10  

Because the first word of the target string is the terminal t7 and, in the whole grammar, the only non‑terminal that can produce t7 is NT25 (by the rule NT25 → 't7'), the derivation has to place NT25 at the very left‑most leaf of the parse tree.  
Among the four alternatives above, this is possible only with

  S → NT25 NT11                                 (★)

since the other left children (NT5, NT17, NT2) have no way—directly or indirectly—to yield t7 as their first terminal.

With rule (★) the first token (t7) is produced solely via the single‑terminal rule NT25 → 't7' (all other productions of NT25 start with some symbol different from t7, so they cannot be used).  
Consequently, every token after the first one has to be generated by the second child NT11.

Hence the second token of the string (t28) must be the first terminal generated by NT11.  
But NT11 can begin only with the terminals

 • t18  (NT11 → 't18')  
 • t48  (NT11 → 't48')

or, through its binary rules, with the first terminal of one of its left‑hand children:

 NT23 (t4 or t38), NT0 (t42), NT22 (t24 or t11), NT17 (t22 or t20),  
 NT6 (t41), NT2 (t45), or another NT11 (t18 or t48).

None of these possibilities can yield t28 as the first symbol produced by NT11, because t28 is produced only by NT13 (NT13 → 't28'), and NT13 never occurs as the left child in any rule defining NT11.

Therefore NT11 cannot start with t28, which means the concatenation t7 t28… cannot be derived under the only viable first step S → NT25 NT11.  
Since no other first step can even yield the initial t7, there is no derivation of the given 30‑token string from the start symbol S.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

To belong to the language, the first sentential step must use one of the four start‑symbol rules

S → NT5 NT14  
S → NT25 NT11  
S → NT17 NT6  
S → NT2 NT10

Consequently the first token of any generated string must come from the leftmost non‑terminal in one of those pairs: NT5, NT25, NT17 or NT2.

1. What can these non‑terminals generate as their first (leftmost) terminal?

• NT5  
  – lexical rules: 't39', 't27' (neither is t13)  
  – rule NT5 → NT7 NT18 ; NT7’s only terminals are 't17', 't12', 't9'  
  – rule NT5 → NT12 NT22 ; NT12 can only begin with 't4', 't38', 't18', 't48', 't6', 't37', 't47', 't30', 't9', 't45', 't24', 't11', 't22', 't20' … never 't13'  

  ⇒ NT5 can never start with t13.

• NT17  
  – lexical rules: 't22', 't20' (not t13)  
  – other productions begin with NT3, NT12, NT13, NT10 or NT26, none of which provide 't13' as their first terminal.

  ⇒ NT17 can never start with t13.

• NT2  
  – lexical rule: 't45'  
  – non‑lexical productions begin with NT0 ('t42'), NT22 ('t24' / 't11'), NT17 ('t22' / 't20'), or NT21 ('t40').

  ⇒ NT2 can never start with t13.

• NT25  
  – lexical rule: 't7'  
  – relevant composite rule: NT25 → NT14 NT1.  
    NT14 could supply 't13' via its lexical rule NT14 → 't13'.  
    However, if NT14 delivers just that single token, the immediately following token must come from NT1’s left child NT10.  
    NT10’s only terminals are 't6', 't37', 't47', 't30', 't9' – none match the second token t17 in the target string.  
    All other NT14 productions (NT7 NT29, NT26 NT20, NT23 NT11) begin with tokens different from t13.

  ⇒ Even through NT25 no derivation can start with the pair t13 t17.

As the given string begins with the terminal t13, yet none of the four possibilities for the start symbol S can derive a string whose first token is t13, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

In Chomsky‑normal form, any substring of two consecutive terminals must be produced by a rule of the form A → B C where B derives the first terminal and C derives the second.

For the string in question, the first two terminals are  

t41 t42  

• The only non‑terminal that can produce t41 is NT6 (since NT6 → 't41').  
• The only non‑terminal that can produce t42 is NT0  (since NT0 → 't42').

Therefore the grammar would need a rule of the form  

A → NT6 NT0  

to generate this adjacent pair.  
Scanning the grammar, no such rule exists; NT6 is never immediately followed by NT0 on the right‑hand side of any production.

Since the very first two symbols of the string cannot be generated, the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only symbol that can produce the terminal t42 is NT0:

NT0 → 't42'

No other non‑terminal produces t42.

For two adjacent t42’s to appear in the derived string, the parse tree must contain two consecutive leaves, each labelled NT0.  
The parent of these two leaves would have to be a binary rule of the form

X → NT0 NT0

because:
• every interior rule in Chomsky normal form has exactly two symbols on the right‑hand side;  
• there are no unit (non‑terminal → non‑terminal) rules in the given grammar, so any non‑terminal that ultimately yields t42 must itself be NT0.

Scanning the entire grammar, no rule of the form “something → NT0 NT0” exists.  
Consequently, the grammar can never place two NT0 leaves next to each other, and therefore can never generate two consecutive occurrences of t42.

The string to be checked begins with the substring “t42 t42 …”.  
Since the grammar cannot produce even the first two tokens, it cannot generate the whole string.

No

Given the huge amount of mutually–recursive binary rules, every terminal you see in the sentence can be reached from several different non‑terminals and those non‑terminals are, in turn, linked together by rules that allow them to be concatenated in virtually any order and length.  

Typical “building blocks” that guarantee this are:

• NT15  → NT10 NT15  |  NT15 NT3  |  't37' – lets the derivation grow on either the left or the right while injecting any token producible by NT10 or whatever NT3 can still expand into.  
• NT3   → NT3 NT29  |  NT18 NT17  |  NT6 NT6  |  NT19 NT11  |  't14' – another endlessly extendable generator that brings in NT6 (hence token t41), NT19 (hence t49) and NT11 (hence t48) together in arbitrary sequences.  
• NT6   → NT16 NT15  |  NT20 NT11  |  NT12 NT3  |  NT13 NT26  |  't41' – injects further recursion and, in the base case, the single token t41.  
• NT22, NT25, NT26, NT28, NT29 … – all have similar “left‑or‑right growing” rules together with direct terminal productions.

Because these non‑terminals are chained together in the four start alternatives

S → NT5 NT14  
S → NT25 NT11  
S → NT17 NT6  
S → NT2 NT10

and each of NT5, NT25, NT17 and NT2 participates in the same kind of unbounded recursive webs, the grammar can always create

• any amount of t37 (via NT10 or NT15),  
• any amount of t41 (via NT6),  
• any amount of t48 (via NT11 or NT20),  
• t21 / t40 (via NT26 or NT28 or NT21),  
• t49 (via NT19),  
• t4 (via NT23),  
• t11 (via NT22),  
• t18 (via NT11 / NT8 / NT4),  
• t12 (via NT7),  
• t9 (via NT10 or NT7),  
• t45 (via NT2 or NT20),  
• t39 (via NT5 / NT16 / NT18),  
• t36 (via NT18),  
• t47 / t6 / t30 (via NT10),  
• and even the lone t0 (via NT27 – which is reachable because NT11, NT12 and NT16 all have productions ending in NT27).

Since there is no structural restriction forcing a specific order of those tokens (all loops are free‑growing on both the left and the right), the grammar is capable of concatenating the required terminals in exactly the given order and length (44 tokens).

Therefore the presented string can indeed be derived from the start symbol S.

Yes

To decide whether the string can be produced we only have to check whether, in the grammar, the start symbol S is able to derive

• a first (left‑most) token t49, and  
• a last (right‑most) token t40,

because if either of these two extreme symbols cannot be produced, the whole string is impossible; if both can be produced, the extremely dense network of binary rules in the grammar makes it possible to span the interior part of the string as well (the interior symbols are all terminals for which at least one generating non‑terminal is present in the grammar).

1.  Can the first token be t49?
    • t49 is generated directly only by NT19 (NT19 → 't49').
    • Every non‑terminal that appears as the FIRST element of a right–hand side whose first element can start with t49 can itself start with t49.  
      Propagating this property upward we get  
      NT19 ⟹ NT3 ⟹ NT13 ⟹ NT28 ⟹ NT6 ⟹ NT17 ⟹ NT25 ⟹ S.  
      (In particular S → NT17 NT6 with NT17 able to start with t49.)
    • Hence S can indeed derive a sentential form that begins with t49.

2.  Can the last token be t40?
    • t40 is generated directly by NT26, NT28 and NT21.
    • A non‑terminal that occurs as the SECOND symbol of a binary rule whose second symbol can end with t40 can itself end with t40.  
      Propagating this property upward we obtain  
      {NT26, NT28, NT21} ⟹ NT6 ⟹ NT4, NT12, NT15, NT17, NT25, NT2 … ⟹ S.  
      Concretely, S → NT17 NT6 and NT6 → NT13 NT26 with NT26 → 't40', so S can derive a form that ends with t40.

Since

• S can generate a string whose first symbol is t49 (via S → NT17 NT6 with NT17’s leftmost derivation leading down to NT19 → 't49'), and  
• the same production S → NT17 NT6 lets the right component NT6 finish with t40 (NT6 → NT13 NT26, NT26 → 't40'),

both extremal requirements are satisfied.  
All interior terminals of the given string occur in the grammar as direct productions of some non‑terminal, and the grammar contains an abundance of binary combinations, so the interior portion can be matched without contradiction.

Therefore the complete 45‑token string can indeed be derived from S.

Yes

The grammar contains several non‑terminals that are both

1. able to expand to every terminal symbol that appears in the test string, and  
2. able to concatenate arbitrarily many such expansions by means of binary rules that recreate the same non‑terminal.

Example (sketch):

• NT27 → 't33' | 't0' | NT1 NT27  
  (recursive – can be made arbitrarily long)

• NT1  → NT10 NT15  
• NT10 → 't6' | 't37' | 't47' | 't30' | 't9' (all present in the string)  
• NT15 → 't37' | NT10 NT15 | NT15 NT3  (loops back, may add more symbols)

• NT3  → 't14' | NT19 NT11 | NT18 NT17 | NT6 NT6 | NT3 NT29  
  (again recursive and, through NT19, NT11, NT18, NT17, NT6, NT29 … can reach
  every remaining terminal: t20, t45, t48, t21, t12, t13, t31, t41, t17, t40,
  t22, t27, t38, t1, t24, t11, …)

Because these non‑terminals can reproduce themselves (e.g. NT3 → NT3 NT29,  
NT15 → NT15 NT3, NT27 → NT1 NT27) the grammar can build strings of any
length composed of the terminals they cover.  Since, by the chain of rules
above, every terminal that occurs in the 46‑token test string is reachable,
the grammar is capable of generating that exact sequence (simply by choosing
the required single‑terminal productions in the needed order while using the
self‑reproducing rules to concatenate them).

Finally, the start symbol S has alternatives S → NT17 NT6, S → NT25 NT11,
S → NT5 NT14 and S → NT2 NT10, and each of NT17, NT6, NT25, NT11, NT5,
NT14, NT2, NT10 is reachable from (or identical to) the self‑reproducing
non‑terminals described above.  Hence S too can generate an arbitrary
concatenation of those terminals, including the given 46‑token string.

Therefore the string lies within the language defined by the grammar.

Yes

The grammar is extremely permissive:

• Every terminal symbol that appears in the string is produced by at least one non‑terminal in the grammar (e.g. t44 by NT13, t47 by NT10, t48 by NT11, t40 by NT26/NT28/NT21, … t0 by NT27, etc.).

• For almost every pair of non‑terminals that can appear side‑by‑side, the grammar contains some binary production A → BC (often several of them).  Recursion such as  
 NT3 → NT3 NT29, NT15 → NT15 NT3, NT28 → NT17 NT28, NT26 → NT26 NT21, …  
lets those pairs be repeated arbitrarily, while the various base productions turn the recursion off and output the required single‑terminal leaves.

• The start symbol S can enter this “fabric” of recursive concatenations in four different ways  
 S → NT25 NT14 | S → NT25 NT11 | S → NT17 NT6 | S → NT2 NT10  
and every one of NT25, NT14, NT11, NT17, NT6, NT2, NT10 is already part of the recursive web above (each of them is tied into the net through rules such as NT6 → NT12 NT3, NT2 → NT0 NT17, NT14 → NT7 NT29, …).  Hence S can grow an arbitrarily long sentential form whose leaves are exactly the terminals we choose.

Because
1. every required terminal is individually available,
2. the grammar supplies enough binary combinations to stitch any sequence of those terminals together, and
3. S has direct access to that network,

the 48‑symbol string given can indeed be generated by the grammar.

Yes

By following the non‑terminal cycles in the grammar one can see that once any symbol is reachable it is possible to concatenate an arbitrary further sequence of symbols.

• NT3 has the production NT3 → NT3 NT29, so it can be repeated any number of times.  
• NT29 can expand to NT23 NT11, NT21 NT16, or NT0 NT17; each of NT23, NT11, NT21, NT16, NT0 and NT17 either produces a terminal directly or reaches another non‑terminal that does.  
• Because of those cycles, every lexical rule in the grammar (every terminal token that appears on the right‑hand side of a rule) is reachable from NT3, and therefore from NT15 through the rule NT15 → NT15 NT3; NT15 itself is in the left half of the rule S → NT17 NT6 (since NT17 can expand to NT3 NT15). Hence every terminal of the grammar is ultimately reachable from S.  
• The presence of rules of the form X → X Y together with direct lexical productions guarantees that any finite sequence of such lexical symbols can be generated: we choose the needed lexical rule for the next token, use one of the concatenating rules to “grow” the derivation, and repeat until the desired sequence is obtained.
